1️⃣ Function parameter: int* age vs int age

When you declare a function:

void birthday(int* age) { ... }


int* age means: “age is a pointer to an int.”

int age would mean: “age is a normal integer value.”

Why use a pointer here?

C passes arguments by value. That means the function gets a copy of whatever you pass.

If you pass int age and increment it inside the function, the original age in main does not change.

By passing a pointer (int* age), you give the function the address of the variable, so it can modify the original.

2️⃣ The * in int* age vs *age

C uses * in two related but different ways:

Context	Meaning
int *age (in declaration)	age is a pointer to an int.
*age (in expression)	Dereference the pointer: get or modify the value it points to.

So in your code:

void birthday(int* age){
    (*age)++;  // increment the value at the memory address
}


*age accesses the value stored at the pointer.

(*age)++ increments that value.

Without the parentheses:

*age++   // increments the pointer itself (moves to next memory location), not the value!


Parentheses ensure you increment the value and not the pointer.




📝 C Increment Cheat Sheet

Assume:

int n = 27;
int *p = &n;

1️⃣ Value increment (*p)
Expression	Pointer moves?	Value changes?		Expression result
(*p)++		❌ no		✅ yes (after)		old value (27)
++(*p)		❌ no		✅ yes (before)		new value (28)

Key: Memory changes in both cases, difference is only what the expression evaluates to.

2️⃣ Pointer increment (p)
Expression	Pointer moves?		Value changes?	Expression result
*p++		✅ yes (after)		❌ no		value at old pointer
*++p		✅ yes (before)		❌ no		value at new pointer

Key: Here the pointer moves, the value is not modified.






3️⃣ Why sometimes int* age and sometimes int *age

Both are syntactically correct:

int* age;   // style 1: “age is a pointer to int”
int *age;   // style 2: same meaning


In C, * binds to the variable, not the type. So:

int* a, b;  // a is a pointer, b is a normal int!
int *a, b;  // same meaning


Most people use int *a to remind themselves that *a must be used to access the value.

4️⃣ In main(), why &age?

& is the address-of operator.

birthday(&age);  // pass the address of age


birthday(pAge); would also work because pAge already stores the address:

int *pAge = &age;
birthday(pAge);  // same thing


Both are equivalent; it’s just a matter of whether you want a separate pointer variable (pAge) or pass the address directly.

✅ Summary Table

Concept			Example			Meaning
Pointer declaration	int* pAge		pAge is a pointer to an int
Pointer dereference	*pAge			Access or modify the int value it points to
Address-of operator	&age			Gives the memory address of age
Pass pointer to func    birthday(&age)		Function can modify original value


1️⃣ Two different uses of *

In C, the * operator is context-sensitive:

Declaration of a pointer

int *p;  // p is a pointer to an int


Here, * tells the compiler: "this variable is a pointer."

Dereferencing a pointer

*p = 5; // write 5 to the memory location p points to
int x = *p; // read the value stored at p


Here, * means: "follow the pointer to get the value."

Notice: these are not the same — one is telling the compiler “this variable is a pointer,” the other is an operator that gets the value it points to.

2️⃣ Passing a pointer to a function

When you call a function, the * is not used in the call, because you are passing the pointer itself, not dereferencing it:

int age = 25;
int *pAge = &age;

birthday(pAge);   // pass the pointer
birthday(&age);   // pass the pointer directly


pAge already stores an address, so you don’t put *pAge here — that would dereference it and pass the value 25, not the address.

&age computes the address of age, which is exactly what the function needs.

3️⃣ Inside the function: using *

Inside the function, you do need * to access the value:

void birthday(int* age) {
    (*age)++;  // increment the value at the pointer
}


age is a pointer to int.

*age is the value it points to.

If you didn’t use *:

age++;  


That would move the pointer itself in memory, not increment the actual age.

4️⃣ General rule of thumb

Think in terms of what type you have:

Situation			What you have	What you want		Do you need *?
Declare a pointer		variable	N/A			* in declaration
Pass pointer to function	pointer		just pass address	no *
Access the value pointed to	pointer		the actual value	yes *
Take address of variable	variable	address			use &






========================================

int x = 42;
int *p = &x;

    p stores the address of x.

    *p accesses the value stored at that address.










======================================

✅ Rule of thumb (VERY important in C)
What you have	What it means				When to use
ptr		address of data				pass to memcpy, send, recv, etc
*ptr		the actual value at that address	when you want to read/write fields
